## Why This Is Asked

Assesses advanced DR design across multiple AWS services, cross-account governance, data consistency, testing rigor, and rollback plans under real-world constraints.

## Key Concepts

- Route 53 failover routing and health checks
- AWS Global Accelerator for fast global routing
- DynamoDB global tables for cross-region writes
- S3 cross-region replication for assets
- IAM boundary policies and per-region KMS keys
- Step Functions / Lambda for orchestration and playbooks
- DR testing, rollback, and cost controls

## Code Example

```javascript
// Minimal Step Functions skeleton for DR orchestration (pseudo-structure)
{
  "Comment": "DR failover workflow",
  "StartAt": "HealthCheck",
  "States": {
    "HealthCheck": {
      "Type": "Task",
      "Resource": "arn:aws:lambda:REGION:ACCOUNT:function:HealthCheck",
      "Next": "Evaluate"
    },
    "Evaluate": {
      "Type": "Choice",
      "Choices": [
        { "Variable": "$.outage", "BooleanEquals": true, "Next": "InitiateFailover" }
      ],
      "Default": "Done"
    },
    "InitiateFailover": {
      "Type": "Task",
      "Resource": "arn:aws:states:::aws-sdk:route53:changeResourceRecordSets",
      "End": true
    },
    "Done": { "Type": "Succeed" }
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you validate RTO/RPO during a simulated outage without impacting customers?
- What metrics and alarms would you attach to the DR workflow to ensure timely detection and rollback readiness?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests knowledge of tenant isolation mechanisms in S3 using Access Points and granular IAM roles, plus organizational governance via SCPs. It also checks practical testing and rollback planning.

## Key Concepts
- S3 Access Points and per-tenant isolation
- IAM roles with least privilege
- Organization SCPs and cross-account boundaries
- Testing isolation and rollback strategies

## Code Example
```javascript
// Per-tenant role policy (conceptual)
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": ["s3:GetObject"],
      "Resource": ["arn:aws:s3:::tenant-data-bucket/tenants/tenantA/*"]
    }
  ]
}
```

```javascript
// Access Point policy (conceptual)
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Principal": {"AWS": "arn:aws:iam::123456789012:role/TenantAAccessRole"},
      "Action": ["s3:GetObject"],
      "Resource": ["arn:aws:s3:us-east-1:123456789012:accesspoint/tenantA-ap/*"]
    }
  ]
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you scale this to 100+ tenants without exploding policy management?
- What are trade-offs of centralizing data in one bucket vs per-tenant buckets?

## Why This Is Asked
Assesss ability to design cross-account governance, immutable logs, and automated remediation in large AWS footprints. The candidate should justify cross-account delivery, object locking, encryption, and monitoring.

## Key Concepts
- Centralized log sink, cross-account delivery, S3 Object Lock; AWS KMS CMK; SCPs; CloudTrail/VPC Flow Logs/Config; EventBridge/Lambda for health checks.
- Testing strategy: staging accounts, dry-run delivery, drift detection, rollback.

## Code Example
```json
{
  "BucketPolicy": {
    "Version": "2012-10-17",
    "Statement": [
      {"Effect": "Allow", "Principal": {"Service": "cloudtrail.amazonaws.com"},"Action": "s3:PutObject","Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::audit-logs-bucket/*"}
    ]
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you validate cross-region delivery latency? 
- How would you handle CMK rotation and SCP exceptions during outages?

